{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015F136fZdaPqrUw6AbDzpsy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 9-2: State schema migration for multi-stack\n     2→\n     3→## Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→## Story\n     6→\n     7→As a developer upgrading codeharness,\n     8→I want my existing state file to auto-migrate to the new multi-stack format,\n     9→So that I don't have to re-initialize.\n    10→\n    11→## Acceptance Criteria\n    12→\n    13→- [x] AC1: Given an old state file with `stack: 'nodejs'` and no `stacks` field, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `['nodejs']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    14→- [x] AC2: Given a new state file with `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `['nodejs', 'rust']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    15→- [x] AC3: Given a state file with neither `stack` nor `stacks`, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `[]` and `state.stack` is `null` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→- [x] AC4: Given state is written via `writeState()` with `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`, when the file is inspected, then it contains both `stacks` array AND `stack: nodejs` for backward compat <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→- [x] AC5: Given `getDefaultState()` is called with a stack argument, then the returned state has both `stack` and `stacks` fields populated consistently <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→- [x] AC6: Given a corrupted state file triggers `recoverCorruptedState()`, then the recovered state has both `stack` and `stacks` fields populated from `detectStack()` and `detectStacks()` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→- [x] AC7: Given `isValidState()` validates state, then it accepts both old-format (only `stack`, no `stacks`) and new-format (both `stack` and `stacks`) state files <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→- [x] AC8: Given the full test suite runs after all changes, then all existing single-stack tests pass with zero regressions <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→\n    22→## Technical Notes\n    23→\n    24→### HarnessState Interface Changes\n    25→\n    26→File: `src/lib/state.ts` — `HarnessState` interface (L7-60).\n    27→\n    28→Add a new `stacks` field after the existing `stack` field:\n    29→\n    30→```ts\n    31→import { detectStack, detectStacks, type StackName } from './stack-detect.js';\n    32→\n    33→export interface HarnessState {\n    34→  harness_version: string;\n    35→  initialized: boolean;\n    36→  stack: string | null;          // kept for backward compat — always stacks[0] ?? null\n    37→  stacks: StackName[];           // NEW — all detected stacks\n    38→  app_type?: 'server' | 'cli' | 'web' | 'agent' | 'generic';\n    39→  // ... rest unchanged\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→The existing import `import { detectStack } from './stack-detect.js'` (L5) must be expanded to include `detectStacks` and `StackName`.\n    44→\n    45→### Migration Logic — `migrateState()` Function\n    46→\n    47→A new private function that normalizes state from any format (old, new, or empty) into the canonical new format:\n    48→\n    49→```ts\n    50→function migrateState(state: HarnessState): HarnessState {\n    51→  const raw = state as Record<string, unknown>;\n    52→\n    53→  // New format: stacks array already present\n    54→  if (Array.isArray(raw.stacks) && raw.stacks.length > 0) {\n    55→    state.stacks = raw.stacks as StackName[];\n    56→    state.stack = state.stacks[0] ?? null;\n    57→    return state;\n    58→  }\n    59→\n    60→  // Old format: has stack string but no stacks array\n    61→  if (typeof raw.stack === 'string' && raw.stack) {\n    62→    state.stacks = [raw.stack as StackName];\n    63→    return state;\n    64→  }\n    65→\n    66→  // Neither present\n    67→  state.stacks = [];\n    68→  state.stack = null;\n    69→  return state;\n    70→}\n    71→```\n    72→\n    73→Apply `migrateState()` in both `readState()` (L130-135) and `readStateWithBody()` (L157-165) after successful YAML parse and `isValidState()` check.\n    74→\n    75→### writeState() Dual-Write\n    76→\n    77→Before YAML serialization, ensure `stack` is always synced from `stacks[0]`:\n    78→\n    79→```ts\n    80→// In writeState(), before stringify:\n    81→if (state.stacks && state.stacks.length > 0) {\n    82→  state.stack = state.stacks[0];\n    83→}\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→This ensures old codeharness versions reading the file still see a valid `stack` field.\n    87→\n    88→### getDefaultState() Update\n    89→\n    90→```ts\n    91→export function getDefaultState(stack?: string | null): HarnessState {\n    92→  return {\n    93→    // ... existing fields ...\n    94→    stack: stack ?? null,\n    95→    stacks: stack ? [stack as StackName] : [],\n    96→    // ... rest unchanged ...\n    97→  };\n    98→}\n    99→```\n   100→\n   101→### isValidState() Update\n   102→\n   103→The current validator (L172-183) checks `s.stack !== null && typeof s.stack !== 'string'`. It must also accept state without `stacks` (old format) and state with `stacks` (new format):\n   104→\n   105→- If `stacks` is present, it must be an array\n   106→- If `stacks` is absent, that's valid (old format — migration will add it)\n   107→\n   108→### recoverCorruptedState() Update\n   109→\n   110→Currently uses `detectStack(dir)` (L187) which returns root-only stack. Update to also call `detectStacks(dir)` and populate `stacks` from all detected stacks:\n   111→\n   112→```ts\n   113→function recoverCorruptedState(dir: string): HarnessState {\n   114→  warn('State file corrupted — recreating from detected config');\n   115→  const stack = detectStack(dir);\n   116→  const allStacks = detectStacks(dir);\n   117→  const state = getDefaultState(stack);\n   118→  // Dedupe: detectStacks may return same stack from multiple dirs\n   119→  const uniqueStackNames = [...new Set(allStacks.map(s => s.stack))];\n   120→  state.stacks = uniqueStackNames;\n   121→  writeState(state, dir);\n   122→  return state;\n   123→}\n   124→```\n   125→\n   126→### InitResult Type Update\n   127→\n   128→File: `src/modules/infra/types.ts` — The `InitResult` interface has `stack: string | null`. Add `stacks: string[]` alongside it. Keep `stack` as `stacks[0] ?? null` for existing consumers.\n   129→\n   130→### Breaking Change Risk\n   131→\n   132→None. All additions are backward-compatible:\n   133→- `stacks` is a new field; old state files auto-migrate on read\n   134→- `stack` is preserved for all existing consumers\n   135→- `isValidState()` accepts both old and new formats\n   136→\n   137→## Files to Change\n   138→\n   139→- `src/lib/state.ts` — Add `stacks: StackName[]` to `HarnessState`, add `migrateState()` function, update `readState()` and `readStateWithBody()` to call migration, update `writeState()` to dual-write, update `getDefaultState()` to populate `stacks`, update `isValidState()` to accept old and new formats, update `recoverCorruptedState()` to use `detectStacks()`, expand import from `./stack-detect.js`\n   140→- `src/modules/infra/types.ts` — Add `stacks: string[]` to `InitResult`, keep `stack` as compat alias\n   141→- `src/lib/__tests__/state.test.ts` — Add migration tests (old→new, new format, neither-field, dual-write, getDefaultState stacks, isValidState both formats, recovery with stacks, round-trip)\n   142→\n   143→## Tasks/Subtasks\n   144→\n   145→- [x] Task 1: Expand import in `state.ts` to include `detectStacks` and `StackName` from `./stack-detect.js`\n   146→- [x] Task 2: Add `stacks: StackName[]` field to `HarnessState` interface (after `stack`)\n   147→- [x] Task 3: Implement `migrateState()` private function that normalizes old/new/empty formats\n   148→- [x] Task 4: Apply `migrateState()` in `readState()` after YAML parse and validation\n   149→- [x] Task 5: Apply `migrateState()` in `readStateWithBody()` after YAML parse and validation\n   150→- [x] Task 6: Update `writeState()` to sync `stack` from `stacks[0]` before serialization\n   151→- [x] Task 7: Update `getDefaultState()` to include `stacks` field\n   152→- [x] Task 8: Update `isValidState()` to accept old-format state (no `stacks`) as valid\n   153→- [x] Task 9: Update `recoverCorruptedState()` to populate `stacks` from `detectStacks()`\n   154→- [x] Task 10: Add `stacks: string[]` to `InitResult` in `src/modules/infra/types.ts`\n   155→- [x] Task 11: Add test — old format migration (`stack: 'nodejs'`, no `stacks`) produces `stacks: ['nodejs']`\n   156→- [x] Task 12: Add test — new format read (`stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`) produces `stack: 'nodejs'`\n   157→- [x] Task 13: Add test — neither field present produces `stacks: []`, `stack: null`\n   158→- [x] Task 14: Add test — `writeState()` dual-write: both `stacks` and `stack` appear in YAML output\n   159→- [x] Task 15: Add test — `getDefaultState()` returns consistent `stack` and `stacks`\n   160→- [x] Task 16: Add test — `isValidState()` accepts both old-format and new-format state objects\n   161→- [x] Task 17: Add test — round-trip: write multi-stack → read → verify both fields intact\n   162→- [x] Task 18: Run full test suite — verify zero regressions\n   163→\n   164→## Dev Agent Record\n   165→\n   166→### Implementation Plan\n   167→- Added `stacks: StackName[]` to `HarnessState` interface with backward-compatible migration\n   168→- `migrateState()` normalizes three formats: old (stack only), new (stacks array), and empty (neither)\n   169→- `writeState()` dual-writes both `stack` and `stacks` for backward compat with older codeharness versions\n   170→- `recoverCorruptedState()` now uses `detectStacks()` to populate multi-stack data\n   171→- `InitResult` type updated with `stacks: string[]` and all construction sites updated\n   172→- Updated test files that construct `HarnessState` literals to include `stacks` field\n   173→\n   174→### Completion Notes\n   175→- All 18 tasks completed. 19 new tests added to state.test.ts (58 total, up from 39).\n   176→- Full test suite: 114 files, 3098 tests, 0 failures.\n   177→- Also updated `retro-import.test.ts` (19 occurrences) and `stack.test.ts` (18 occurrences) to include `stacks` field in mock state objects.\n   178→- Updated `init-project.ts` to populate `stacks` from `detectStacks()` during init and rerun paths.\n   179→\n   180→## File List\n   181→\n   182→- `src/lib/state.ts` — Added `stacks: StackName[]` to interface, `migrateState()` function, updated `readState`, `readStateWithBody`, `writeState`, `getDefaultState`, `isValidState`, `recoverCorruptedState`\n   183→- `src/modules/infra/types.ts` — Added `stacks: string[]` to `InitResult`\n   184→- `src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` — Added `detectStacks` import, populated `stacks` in init and rerun paths\n   185→- `src/lib/__tests__/state.test.ts` — Added 19 migration tests in \"Multi-stack state migration\" describe block\n   186→- `src/commands/__tests__/retro-import.test.ts` — Added `stacks: ['nodejs']` to 19 mock state objects\n   187→- `src/commands/__tests__/stack.test.ts` — Added `stacks` field to 18 mock state objects, imported `StackName` type\n   188→\n   189→## Change Log\n   190→\n   191→- 2026-03-23: Implemented state schema migration for multi-stack support (story 9-2). Added `stacks: StackName[]` field, migration logic, dual-write backward compat, and 19 new tests. Zero regressions across 3098 tests.\n   192→- 2026-03-23: Code review fixes — (1) init-project.ts now persists multi-stacks to state file, (2) writeState no longer mutates input state object, (3) isValidState rejects stacks arrays with non-string elements, (4) recoverCorruptedState explicitly syncs stack from stacks[0]. Added 2 new tests (3100 total). Coverage 97.03%, all files above 80%.\n   193→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01NquLEscKgNYqRefYHqoXxE","session_id":"46c7b24e-5b3f-4eb1-bc5a-20f6a0336cfe","uuid":"bcc29486-6f2d-4473-a27f-a54c6f48632a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:48:51.609Z"}
