{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0194nRgPNTaLmtv3stqVM6RT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01D3mhk5wqmDG5iSA6jDyttQ","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-9-3-init-orchestrator-per-stack-iteration && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"$(cat <<'VERIFYPROMPT'\nYou are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness init --json`\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- `codeharness` — the project CLI\n- `claude` — Claude Code CLI (authenticated via ANTHROPIC_API_KEY env var)\n- `curl`, `jq` — for querying observability endpoints\n- `node`, `npm` — Node.js runtime\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): `http://localhost:9428`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): `http://localhost:8428`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): `http://localhost:16686`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\n- If the response contains one or more log entries, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains zero log entries, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag: `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `verification/9-3-init-orchestrator-per-stack-iteration-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```text\n## AC N: <description>\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`** — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** — there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. **Report REAL failures** — if a feature does not work via the CLI or the documentation is insufficient to exercise it, report that as a verification failure.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** — reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.**\n6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** — physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems are NOT valid escalation reasons.\n7. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL].\n\n## Important Context for This Story\n\nThis story is about `codeharness init` supporting multi-stack projects. To verify:\n1. Create a multi-stack project inside the container (a directory with both `package.json` and `Cargo.toml`)\n2. Run `codeharness init` on it\n3. Check that coverage tools are detected for each stack\n4. Check that OTLP packages are referenced for each stack\n5. Check that info messages list all detected stacks\n6. Check that state file has correct `stacks` array\n\nUse `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '...'` for multi-line setup commands.\nVERIFYPROMPT\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Run verifier session in clean workspace","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":348,"cache_read_input_tokens":53818,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":348},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"46c7b24e-5b3f-4eb1-bc5a-20f6a0336cfe","uuid":"e76bc58c-0450-4260-8163-97e97710cd3c"}
